<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="508" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,331,682]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Remarks.</emphasis>
The specimens that we have examined closely match the original description provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen, N. M." pageId="1" pageNumber="508" pagination="253 - 268" refId="ref7414" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1983) The Old World Microveliinae (Hemiptera: Veliidae). I. The status of Pseudovelia Hoberlandt and Perivelia Poisson, with a review of Oriental species. Entomologica Scandinavica, 14, 253 - 268. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631283 X 00254" type="journal article" year="1983">Andersen (1983)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[243,478,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[243,478,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Pseudovelia buccula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by its posteriorly produced buccula, long hairs on the ventral part of the middle femur (
<figureCitation box="[446,530,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
), and relatively long and curved hind tarsal segment I (
<figureCitation box="[1159,1245,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). The depression of abdominal segment VIII of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1983" box="[492,608,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="buccula">
<emphasis box="[492,608,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">P. buccula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is nearly rectangular, with four small tufts of setae along its margin (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,226,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,211,1681]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 35. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 36. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 37. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 38. P. plauta sp. nov.; 39. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 40. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816737/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Figs. 35</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[194,224,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,216,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[151,1436,211,1738]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 41–46. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 41. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 42. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 43. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 44. P. plauta sp. nov.; 45. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 46. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816739/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">41</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[237,267,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,201,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[151,1436,181,1808]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 47. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 48. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 49. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 50. P. plauta sp. nov.; 51. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 52. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816743/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">47</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[280,311,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–58" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,182,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-21@12.[151,1436,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 53–58. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 53. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 54. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 55. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 56. P. plauta sp. nov.; 57. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 58. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816745" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816745/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">53</figureCitation>
). The hind margin of the pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[738,821,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">Fig. 59</figureCitation>
) bears dense, short, brown setae. This is a new record for 
<collectingCountry box="[191,262,619,645]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="508">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
